snulý","1114–Female":"1114–Zesnulá","–Female":"Zesnulá","1090":"1090","before 1114":"před 1114","1114":"1114","about 1114":"okolo 1114","Of,Seagrave,Leicestershire,England":"Seagrave, Leicestershire, Anglie, United Kingdom","Europe":"Europe"},"da":{"–":"Afdød","1090–Male":"1090–Afdød","1114–Female":"1114–Afdød","–Female":"Afdød","1090":"1090","before 1114":"før 1114","1114":"1114","about 1114":"omkring 1114","Of,Seagrave,Leicestershire,England":"Seagrave, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom","Europe":"Europe"},"nl":{"–":"Overleden","1090–Male":"1090–Overleden","1114–Female":"1114–Overleden","–Female":"Overleden","1090":"1090","before 1114":"vóór 1114","1114":"1114","about 1114":"circa 1114","Of,Seagrave,Leicestershire,England":"Seagrave, Leicestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Europe":"Europa"},"en":{"–":"Deceased","1090–Male":"1090–Deceased","1114–Female":"1114–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1090":"1090","before 1114":"before 1114","1114":"1114","about 1114":"about 1114","Of,Seagrave,Leicestershire,England":"Seagrave, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom","Europe":"Europe","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Spencer","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): occupational name for someone who dispensed provisions or money, from Middle English <i>spenser(e)</i>, <i>spencer(e)</i> ‘household steward, butler, almoner’ (Anglo-Norman French <i>espenser</i>, Old French <i>despensier</i>). Compare   Spence   and   Spender  . There is some dispute about the origins of the Spencer family, whose most famous member in recent times was the late Princess of Wales, born Lady Diana Spencer (1961–97). Some sources say that they are descended from William the Conqueror's steward, Robert Despencer. What is clear is that by the 15th century they had become prosperous from sheep farming in Northamptonshire. Robert Spencer (died 1627) was said to be the wealthiest man in England. Their titles have included Earls of Sunderland and Earls Spencer; and through the female line the 5th Earl of Sunderland also became Duke of Marlborough in 1733. This connection was the result of the marriage, in 1700, of the 3rd Duke of Sunderland to the daughter of John Churchill, 1st Duke of Marlborough. The youngest son of this union, John Spencer (1708–46), was the father of the 1st Earl Spencer (1734–83)."],"variants":[{"name":"Spence","meanings":["English and Scottish: nickname for a servant employed in the pantry of a great house or monastery, from Middle English <i>spense</i>, <i>spence</i> ‘pantry, larder, storeroom’ (Old French <i>despense</i>, from a Late Latin derivative of <i>dispendere</i>, past participle <i>dispensus</i> ‘to weigh out or dispense’). Compare   Spencer  ."]},{"name":"Spenser","meanings":["English: variant of   Spencer  ."]},{"name":"Spender","meanings":["English:","occupational name or status name from Middle English <i>spender(e)</i>, <i>spendour</i> ‘steward, treasurer’, a shortened form of Middle English, Old French <i>despendour</i>, denoting someone who managed money or supplies. Compare   Spencer  .","alternatively, perhaps a nickname from Middle English <i>spender(e)</i>, <i>spendour</i> ‘spender (of money), spendthrift’."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Thomas De Spencer married Thomas De Spencer before 1114, in Europe. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","1090–Male":"1090–Surnud","1114–Female":"1114–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1090":"1090","before 1114":"enne 1114","1114":"1114","about 1114":"umbes 1114","Of,Seagrave,Leicestershire,England":"Seagrave, Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Europe":"Europe"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","1090–Male":"1090–Kuollut","1114–Female":"1114–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1090":"1090","before 1114":"ennen vuotta 1114","1114":"1114","about 1114":"noin 1114","Of,Seagrave,Leicestershire,England":"Seagrave, Leicestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Europe":"Europe"},"fr":{"–":"Décédée","1090–Male":"1090–Décédé","1114–Female":"1114–Décédée","–Female":"Décédée","1090":"1090","before 1114":"avant 1114","1114":"1114","about 1114":"environ 1114","Of,Seagrave,Leicestershire,England":"Seagrave, Leicestershire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Europe":"Europe","lifeSummary":"Mrs Thomas De Spencer a épousé Thomas De Spencer avant 1114, à Europe. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fille."},"de":{"–":"Verstorben","1090–Male":"1090–Verstorben","1114–Female":"1114–Verstorben","–Female":"Verstorben","1090":"1090","before 1114":"vor 1114","1114":"1114","about 1114":"um 1114","Of,Seagrave,Leicestershire,England":"Seagrave, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom","Europe":"Europa","lifeSummary":"Mrs Thomas De Spencer hat vor 1114 in Europa Thomas De Spencer